✅ 1. Support & Stability (MOST IMPORTANT)
4.7 is deprecated / unsupported
4.10 is actively supported by Red Hat
👉 Why important:
Security patches
Bug fixes
Vendor support
✅ 2. Better Vulnerability Detection (CVEs)
👉 CVEs = Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (security issues)
New version has updated vulnerability database
Detects more and latest security issues
👉 Meaning:
Same image → more accurate results in 4.10
✅ 3. Improved Scanner (Accuracy + Speed)
Better image scanning engine
Faster scans
Fewer false positives
👉 Benefit:
More reliable security reports
✅ 4. Kubernetes / OpenShift Compatibility
4.10 supports newer OpenShift/K8s versions
4.7 may break in future upgrades
👉 Benefit:
Future-proof platform
✅ 5. Database Upgrade (Postgres 13 → 15)
Better performance
Faster queries
Improved reliability
👉 Benefit:
Faster UI, reports, queries
✅ 6. New Features (High-level)
Delegated scanning improvements
Better policy management
Improved UI & usability
Better cluster health visibility
✅ 7. Security Enhancements
Stronger TLS/security defaults
Better RBAC and access control
⚡ One-Line Impact Statement (VERY IMPORTANT)
👉 If manager asks impact:
This upgrade improves security visibility, ensures platform supportability, and provides more accurate vulnerability detection across all clusters.
🎤 If they ask “Why now?”
Because 4.7 is nearing end of support, and upgrading now avoids future risks, ensures compliance, and keeps our security platform up to date.
🧠 Your Internal Understanding (VERY IMPORTANT)
👉 Upgrade is NOT just version change
It improves:
Detection (CVEs)
Performance
Stability
Compatibility
✅ Short version (if they want quick answer)
We are upgrading to stay on a supported version, improve vulnerability detection, enhance performance, and ensure compatibility with newer OpenShift environments.
